  "doc_id": "42744",
  "text": "As a general inhibitor, which targets diverse formin isoforms with similar potency, SMIFH2 may be a useful drug for identifying cellular processes dependent on formin-mediated actin assembly in a broad range of experimental systems. However, it will be important to isolate formin isoform-specific inhibitors to determine which formin is required for a particular cellular process. Furthermore, particular formin isoforms are involved in malignant tumor formation and are highly overexpressed in a range of cancer cell types [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Isoform-specific inhibitors are likely to be better anti-metastatic tumor drugs because they may target tumor cells while having less impact on surrounding healthy tissues.",
